{
  "texts": [
    "At lower replacement levels (5% to 20%), FA has varied effects, with a 10% replacement increasing flexural strength by 27.5%.",
    "At higher levels (20% to 80%), compressive strength initially declines, but there is a slight improvement at 40% and a recovery of 30% at 80%.",
    "Combining (HFFA) with Class F FA at replacement levels of 5% to 15% results in decreased mechanical properties, with reductions of 20% and 35% at 10% and 15% replacement levels, respectively, indicating a negative impact on concrete strength as per Georgiou et al. [59].",
    "Saand et al. [60]found that replacing cement with RHA at levels between 2.5% and 15% by weight significantly increased mechanical strength, with compressive strength rising by 22.22% and split tensile strength by 20.45% at a 10% replacement.",
    "Similarly, Kanthe et al. [61] reported an improvement in compressive strength of 5.56% at a 10% RHA replacement level and 7.5% at a 50% replacement level, even without superplasticizers, suggesting that RHA can effectively enhance concrete strength on its own."
  ]
}